    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my physics final and im kinda stuck on quantum entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? i dont need the heavy math right now just a conceptual explanation",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two particles become linked and the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance between them. This is unlike classical correlation, where objects can only be correlated if they have interacted in the past, so classical physics can't explain instant correlations over long distances. Entanglement is a unique and fundamental aspect of quantum physics that challenges our classical understanding of the world.",
