    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it still feels really weird. i read somewhere that Einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it's so hard to wrap your head around. can you explain why he called it spooky? like what is it about the connection that makes it seem so unnatural compared to how normal things work?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein used the term \"spooky action at a distance\" to express his discomfort with the idea of entanglement because it seems to violate the principle that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light. In classical physics, objects only affect one another through direct interaction or through forces, obeying a local-speed limit. Entanglement appears to cause instantaneous changes between entangled particles, which suggests that they instantly affect each other no matter how far apart they are, without any known mechanism. Einstein was uneasy with this, as it contradicted his beliefs in locality, macroscopic realism, and realism—the idea that in the real physical world, objects have definite properties (realism). The phenomenon of entanglement lies at the heart of the tension between classical concepts of reality and the non-locality, non-reality, and reflection-free nature of the quantum world, which is why Einstein chose such a strong word to describe it.",
      "source": "target",
